<span id="freeTextContainer12661411389193074548">Will likely vacillate between 4 and 5 stars but wow a little too much truth unvarnished. What might have been considered some sort of wild-eyed conspiracy tome 12 years ago; ages into an all too plausible explanation. Ugh. More thoughts to follow...<br/><br/>---------------------------------------<br/>Updated 5/20/2020<br/><br/>Never wrote a proper review but I had good notes from reading. Just posting my my notes..<br/><br/>· Very prescient<br/>· Klein starts with immoral medical experiments to set the stage<br/>	o Theory was that to cure</span>
  <span id="freeText12661411389193074548" style="display:none">Will likely vacillate between 4 and 5 stars but wow a little too much truth unvarnished. What might have been considered some sort of wild-eyed conspiracy tome 12 years ago; ages into an all too plausible explanation. Ugh. More thoughts to follow...<br /><br />---------------------------------------<br />Updated 5/20/2020<br /><br />Never wrote a proper review but I had good notes from reading. Just posting my my notes..<br /><br />· Very prescient<br />· Klein starts with immoral medical experiments to set the stage<br />	o Theory was that to cure mentally ill patience was the desire to erase their experiences from the mind.  Blank the mind and start over<br />		§ This was done through sensory deprivation, shock therapy and psychotropic drugs<br />	o Results were that it made patients worse, but they had no memory of why just instinctive responses that seemed crazy.<br />	o Particularly immoral because the experimentation was carried out on mental patience without consent.  In fact that's why they were chosen.  Consent was given by the very act of seeking help.<br />· Klein goes into the background of Milton Friedman and the Chicago School of Economics Theory of Free Markets - -  familiar via libertarian<br />	o Notion that no interference from government is necessary.  A totally free market, free of regulation and social interest  is the best option.<br />	o Man is motivated only by greed and thus Democracy is an unnatural state meaning the promotion of the public over individual self interest is putting unnecessary caps on profits.<br />· Klein lays out where she thinks these theories have been employed.  Her theory is that free market requires a lack of regulation that would never play in democratic societies so the idea is to have a disaster or crisis that allows for the stripping of regulation (erasing of the mind) and unfettered capitalism to flourish.  The theory being that everyone is enriched.<br />· Lots of places where these tactics have been employed <br />	o Chile<br />	o Argentina <br />		§ Falkland's<br />	o Iraq<br />	o Russia<br />	o Chechnya<br />	o New Orleans (Katrina)<br />· It's been failures and yet this theory/philosophy hasn't died.  The reason appears to be greed.  In the face of facts, the very rich have a chance to grab more and they control the governments.  It's scary because it is what is happening today in the US completely.  Using Racism, sexism and bigotry to secure votes, the real idea is to create a disaster and then fix by deregulation and an unfettered capitalism.  To some extent the GOP has just been doing it.  They are creating the disaster by employing their methods. They are deregulating without cause through their agencies.<br />· Taken in context with everything that is happening today is what catapulted this book to a 5 for me.<br />	o Puerto Rico<br />	o Israel (Jerusalem)<br />	o Syria<br />	o Russia<br />	o Brexit<br />	o North Korea<br />	o Climate Change<br />	o Build a Wall<br />	o Immigration<br />	o Tax cut<br />	o Deficit expansion under a Repub president<br />	o Attempted manufactured crisis<br />	o Trump (and Republican donor) enrichment<br />	o Emptying out the federal government (federal jobs are going vacant for very long periods of time losing institutional knowledge)<br /><br /><i>4.5 Stars</i><br /><br />Listened to the Audiobook. Narrated by Jennifer Wiltsie who was excellent.</span>
