        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1804321056" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14387020206106258400">Not sure how much more piercing looks I can take into America&apos;s rotten, blackened core, but that is due more to fatigue than to any criticism I had of this book. Klein presents to us a world that is so paralyzed and bamboozled by entropy and bureaucracy that the only way to catalyze meaningful change is to either take advantage of or foment massive disasters--whether in terms of disaster response, warfare, or regime change. She starts with Allende&apos;s Chile, as all books of this ilk do, and moves </span>
  <span id="freeText14387020206106258400" style="display:none">Not sure how much more piercing looks I can take into America's rotten, blackened core, but that is due more to fatigue than to any criticism I had of this book. Klein presents to us a world that is so paralyzed and bamboozled by entropy and bureaucracy that the only way to catalyze meaningful change is to either take advantage of or foment massive disasters--whether in terms of disaster response, warfare, or regime change. She starts with Allende's Chile, as all books of this ilk do, and moves on to show how blights as diverse as Putin, apartheid Israel, post-Katrina New Orleans, and post-Bush II Baghdad are interlinked, less outliers than harbingers of our coming norms. The "Green Zone" of Baghdad in particular stuck me as baleful, especially juxtaposed with Sandy Springs, GA, its analogue in our own country. <br /><br />Could things get so divided by class, government so privatized, and safety so compromised that we all end up in Atwood-esque compounds determined by our socioeconomic status? Klein at least makes a case for how we might. I suppose we'll have a better idea tomorrow when the election is (hopefully) over for good, but the diverse group of 100+ people who were waiting outline my polling place at 6am in uncontested Brooklyn, NY gives me at least some hope that this outcome can be avoided...</span>
  <a data-text-id="14387020206106258400" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


