  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_11581639" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/11581639" />
    <a title="Naeem" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/217489-naeem"><img alt="Naeem" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1186230499p2/217489.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/11581639?book_show_action=true">Jan 03, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Naeem" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Naeem" href="/user/show/217489-naeem">Naeem</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">those who like Chomsky, Parenti, and Polanyi</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Naeem by: </span>
      paul puhr
  </div>


    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer11581639" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3375729218346061226">The mid-book review (see below) holds up. I have finished the book and it is not a good book. It is a great book. Klein has really achieved something here. Politics, economics, international relations, culture, ideology, and the human capacity to resist domination -- all come together here. <br/><br/>Klein&apos;s global range and tremendous detail are really heartening to me. <br/><br/>Below is the mid-book review written a few days ago: <br/><br/>I am up to chapter 11 (out of 22). So this is a mid-book review.<br/><br/>There is much more </span>
  <span id="freeText3375729218346061226" style="display:none">The mid-book review (see below) holds up. I have finished the book and it is not a good book. It is a great book. Klein has really achieved something here. Politics, economics, international relations, culture, ideology, and the human capacity to resist domination -- all come together here. <br /><br />Klein's global range and tremendous detail are really heartening to me. <br /><br />Below is the mid-book review written a few days ago: <br /><br />I am up to chapter 11 (out of 22). So this is a mid-book review.<br /><br />There is much more here than meets the eye at first glance. Klein writes with elegant economy. I think high school students could read this with comfort. <br /><br />I mention the writing first because the clarity of the prose might lead some to believe that this is a theoretically thin journalistic account. It is not. I think Klein is working out two levels of theory.<br /><br />Level One: This is global political economy at its best. I have not seen something so ambitious since L.S. Stavrianos' <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/271171.Global_Rift" title="Global Rift by L.S. Stavrianos" rel="nofollow noopener">Global Rift</a>. Klein's historical reach is not as great -- she only goes back to the last century. So what is she doing? <br /><br />She is showing how difficult everyday human beings make it for those who want to implement "pure capitalism." Real humans resist pure market economics by practicing all kinds of resistance. This means that pure market economics cannot be implemented in normal conditions. The theorist who shows these ideas the most powerfully is Karl Polanyi in his <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53981.The_Great_Transformation" title="The Great Transformation by Karl Polanyi" rel="nofollow noopener">The Great Transformation: The Political and Economic Origins of Our Time</a>. So we might say that Klein is developing a Polanyi-esque theory of how society tames markets. <br /><br />But what Klein is really showing is the inverse of what Polanyi showed. She shows what must be done so that, despite the resistance of everyday humans, pure market economics is STILL implemented. How is it done? Klein's answer: through a systematic policy of creating shock and awe in a person, a society, and an economy. <br /><br />She traces the origins of this policy and than shows how it is implemented in country after country. The result for me is that the history of the planet (say the last 40 years of it) instead of being splotches of data , come together in a vast but very simple pattern (similar to what happens when you read Stavrianos). Beautifully astonishing.<br /><br />Second Level: perhaps at its deepest this book as a critique of epistemology. Electric shock therapy, shock and awe (as in Iraq), and the implementation of pure market economics have one thing in common. They require a belief in a kind of "state of nature," "tabula rasa," a "clean slate," "terra nullius." See Sven Lindqvist's masterful <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/335803.Terra_Nullius_A_Journey_Through_No_One_s_Land" title="Terra Nullius A Journey Through No One's Land by Sven Lindqvist" rel="nofollow noopener">Terra Nullius</a>.<br /><br />The key idea of modernity is that the mind, the society, an economic culture are incidental elements grafted upon some essential (and blank) thing. If one believes this then we can imagine doing away with those grafted elements we don't like, getting to the blank core, and rebuilding the things we like onto that blank core. <br /><br />Does that sound like development? Like education? Like the idealism of empire (and the empire of idealism?) [insert evil laugh here.:]<br /><br />What Klein shows is that: (1) to do away with the grafted elements is to do away with the essence; the grafted elements are the core; there is no essence,"layers are all there is" (Klien, 372); (2) even with electro shock therapy, even with shock and awe, even with the forced effort to induce pure markets, there is always (yes always) resistance. (Thus returning us to Polanyi's insights). <br /><br />But the epistemological insight here is most important, namely that we are our memories, our history, our culture. We are the effect of influences we acquire by moving through time and space. If layers are all there is then what we are, our very being, is simply those layers.<br /><br />The state of nature, tabula rasa, the garden of Eden -- these are all ways to evade the power and burden of process. These are methods of trying to ignore the wounds of historical process. Creating the state of nature for Europeans of the 16th and 17th century was a way to avoid having to think about the massive religious violence from which Europe had just emerged. Would they have been so eager to build the state of nature if they knew that their creation would inspire its own massive violence? Such are the precarious imbalances of long-term history.<br /><br /><br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="3375729218346061226" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


